[23:49:49] Running independent code review...
DECISION: REQUEST_CHANGES

SUMMARY: The workspace tagging and CLI admin subcommands are implemented correctly and tests pass at 75.42% coverage. Two blocking spec deviations remain: API keys are not persisted (in-memory only, lost on restart), and RBAC is only enforced on the three new admin key management endpoints — not on paste creation or retrieval as the acceptance criteria require.

FEEDBACK:
- **[BLOCKING] API keys are in-memory only — lost on restart** (`src/server/api_keys.rs`): The issue spec explicitly requires "Keys stored in SQLite (hashed with Argon2id)". The implementation uses `ApiKeyStore` backed by `RwLock<HashMap>`. Every server restart wipes all created API keys, making the feature unusable for any self-hosted deployment that restarts the process (deploys, crashes, etc.). Fix: persist keys to SQLite (the `rusqlite` crate is already added to `Cargo.toml`). If SQLite is deferred, the PR should be blocked until persistence exists or the spec is formally relaxed.

- **[BLOCKING] RBAC not enforced on paste create/read/delete endpoints** (`src/server/handlers.rs`): Acceptance criteria state "Role-based access control enforced on all endpoints." The `ApiKeyAuth` guard is attached only to the three admin key management routes (`admin_create_key_api`, `admin_list_keys_api`, `admin_revoke_key_api`). The core paste endpoints — `create_api` (`POST /api/pastes`), `show_route`, `raw_route`, and deletion — have no `ApiKeyAuth` parameter. Concretely, a write-scope API key cannot create a paste via the new key system; it must use the old `COPYPASTE_AUTH_TOKEN` env var. Fix: add `ApiKeyAuth` as a parameter to `create_api` and enforce `ApiScope::Write` there; add `ApiScope::Read` enforcement on `show_route`/`raw_route` when auth is enabled; gate paste deletion on `ApiScope::Admin` or ownership.

- **[MINOR] `workspace_paste_list_api` has no authentication** (`src/server/handlers.rs`, `#[get("/api/pastes?<query..>")]`): This endpoint returns a full list of paste IDs and URLs — even without a workspace filter — with no credentials required. Anyone who can reach the server can enumerate all active paste IDs. Fix: either require `ApiScope::Read` via `ApiKeyAuth` or, at minimum, only allow listing when `COPYPASTE_AUTH_TOKEN` is not set (open instance), mirroring what other read endpoints do.
